To put the given equation in slope-intercept form, we can solve it for $y$:

\begin{align*}
4x+2y&=8 \\
2y&=-4x+8 \\
y&=-2x+4.
\end{align*}A parallel line will have the same slope of $-2,$ so its equation will be of the form $y = -2x + b,$ where $b$ is the $y$-intercept.  To determine $b,$ we can substitute the coordinates of the point $(0,1)$ into the equation $y = -2x + b:$

\[1 = -2(0) + b.\]We find $b = 1,$ so the equation of the line is $\boxed{y = -2x + 1}.$

[asy]
unitsize (0.5 cm);

pair A, B, C;

A = (0,4);
B = (0,1);
C = (7,0);

draw((-1,0)--(8,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,5));
draw(graph(-2*x + 4,-1,7),red);
draw(graph(-2*x + 1,-1,7),blue);
draw((0,-1.5)--(1,-1.5)--(1,-1),dashed);

dot("$y = -2x + 4$", (7,-2), SW, UnFill);
dot("$y = -2x + 1$", (3,5), SW, UnFill);
dot("$y = -1.5x + 1$", (0,-1.5), S, UnFill);
dot("$(0,1)$", B, NW);
[/asy]
